Fully charmed tetraquark production at the LHC experiments

Ilia Belov ilia.belov@ge.infn.it INFN, Sezione di Genova, Via Dodecaneso 33, I-16146 Genova, Italy    Alessandro Giachino Departamento de Física Teórica and IFIC, Centro Mixto Universidad de Valencia-CSIC, Parc Científic UV, C/ Catedrático José Beltrán, 2, 46980 Paterna, Spain    Elena Santopinto INFN, Sezione di Genova, Via Dodecaneso 33, I-16146 Genova, Italy
Abstract

We develop the formalism for production of a fully heavy tetraquark and apply it to the calculation of p​p→T4​c+X→𝑝𝑝subscript𝑇4𝑐𝑋pp\to T_{4c}+X cross-sections. We demonstrate that the production cross-section of a fully heavy tetraquark, even if it is a diquark-antidiquark cluster, can be obtained in the meson-like basis, for which the spin-color projection technique is well established. Prompted by the recent LHCb, ATLAS and CMS data, we perform a pQCD calculation of 𝒪​(αs5)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠5{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{5}) short-distance factors in the dominant channel of gluon fusion, and match these to the four-body T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} wave functions in order to obtain the unpolarized T4​c​(0++,1+−,2++)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript0absentsuperscript1absentsuperscript2absentT_{4c}(0^{++},1^{+-},2^{++}) cross-sections. The novelty in comparison with the recently published article Feng et al. (2023) lies in the fact that we predict the absolute values as well as the d​σ/d​pT𝑑𝜎𝑑subscript𝑝𝑇d\sigma/dp_{T} spectra in the kinematic ranges accessible at the ongoing LHC experiments. From the comparison with the signal yield at LHCb we derive the constraints on the Φ⋅Br​(J/ψ​J/ψ)⋅ΦBr𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓\Phi\cdot\text{Br}(J/\psi\,J/\psi) (reduced wave function times branching) product for the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} candidates for X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) and observe that X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) is compatible with a 2++​(2​S)superscript2absent2𝑆2^{++}(2S) state.

I Introduction

The 2020 LHCb discovery of a narrow structure near 6900​MeV6900MeV6900\,\rm MeV in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi invariant mass spectrum Aaij et al. (2020) inaugurated the experimental era of the fully heavy tetraquark states. The mass and width of this state, named X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900), have been measured as M=(6886±11±11)​MeV𝑀plus-or-minus68861111MeVM=(6886\pm 11\pm 11)\;\text{MeV} and Γ=(168±33±69)​MeVΓplus-or-minus1683369MeV\Gamma=(168\pm 33\pm 69)\;\text{MeV} Aaij et al. (2020). In addition to the X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) state, the LHCb collaboration also reported evidence of two additional structures in the same decay channel, peaking at approximately 6400 MeV and 7200 MeV. LHCb also measured the production ratio ℛℛ\mathcal{R}, defined as the number of X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) signal events over the total number of di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi events, ℛ=N(X(6900)→J/ψJ/ψ)):Ntot(J/ψJ/ψ)\mathcal{R}=N(X(6900)\to J/\psi\,J/\psi)):N_{\textrm{tot}}(J/\psi\,J/\psi), where Ntot​(J/ψ​J/ψ)subscript𝑁tot𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓N_{\textrm{tot}}(J/\psi\,J/\psi) is the sum of the background and signal Aaij et al. (2020). The background represents J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi-pairs, either promptly produced or originating as feed-down components from higher charmonium states.

Later, ATLAS also observed a significant excess of events over the total background in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum. As well as confirming the X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900), ATLAS reported a broad structure starting from the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi threshold with a global statistical significance far exceeding 5​σ5𝜎5\,\sigma. ATLAS also explored the J/ψ​ψ​(2​S)𝐽𝜓𝜓2𝑆J/\psi\,\psi(2S) decay channel and reported an additional peak not seen in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mode, with statistical significance larger than 3​σ3𝜎3\,\sigma Aad et al. (2023).

Recently, CMS investigated the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum and confirmed the previously discovered X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) state Hayrapetyan et al. (2024). In that work Hayrapetyan et al. (2024), the CMS collaboration found two new states, namely the X​(6600)𝑋6600X(6600) and X​(7300)𝑋7300X(7300) states, with 6.96.96.9 and 4.74.74.7 standard deviations, respectively.

Up to 2023, investigation of the fully heavy tetraquark production was guided by implementation of the 𝒪​(αs4)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠4{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{4}) matrix elements squared for the hard scattering reaction Berezhnoy et al. (2011, 2012); Maciuła et al. (2021); Zhu (2021); Becchi (2022) and, moreover, normalization of the model-dependent parameters that describe the four-quark hadronization relied on qualitative considerations.

In fact, the first courageous attempts to estimate the fully heavy tetraquark production cross-sections were made in 2011 Berezhnoy et al. (2011, 2012). In those studies the authors calculated the g​g→|c​c⟩3¯⊗|c¯​c¯⟩3→𝑔𝑔tensor-productsubscriptket𝑐𝑐¯3subscriptket¯𝑐¯𝑐3gg\to|cc\rangle_{\bar{3}}\otimes|\bar{c}\bar{c}\rangle_{3} matrix elements and used Pythia to generate a pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} smearing induced by the Initial State Radiation (ISR). Using duality relations, they predicted a qualitative shape of σ​(p​p→T4​c→J/ψ​J/ψ)𝜎→𝑝𝑝subscript𝑇4𝑐→𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓\sigma(pp\to T_{4c}\to J/\psi\,J/\psi) distributions in the approximation of a point-like diquark-antidiquark coupled to a T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c}. In 2021, the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} production mechanism was studied at 𝒪​(αs4)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠4\mathcal{O}(\alpha_{s}^{4}) order by means of the kTsubscript𝑘𝑇k_{T}-factorization approach describing hadronization in the Color Evaporation Model (CEM) Maciuła et al. (2021). Nevertheless, in CEM the probability of c​c¯​c​c¯→T4​c→𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐subscript𝑇4𝑐c\bar{c}c\bar{c}\to T_{4c} transition, which is crucial to obtaining some quantitative predictions, does not come from first principles rather it was estimated by trying to reproduce the LHCb signal-to-background ratio measured in Aaij et al. (2020). Both Single Parton Scattering (SPS) and Double Parton Scattering (DPS) mechanisms were taken into account in estimating the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi background. In Zhu (2021) the low pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} limit, pT≪m4​cmuch-less-thansubscript𝑝𝑇subscript𝑚4𝑐p_{T}\ll m_{4c}, of the inclusive σ​(p​p→T4​c+X)𝜎→𝑝𝑝subscript𝑇4𝑐𝑋\sigma(pp\to T_{4c}+X) cross-section was estimated from the σ​(p​p→T4​c)𝜎→𝑝𝑝subscript𝑇4𝑐\sigma(pp\to T_{4c}) cross-section with the help of Transverse-Momentum-Dependent (TMD) factorization. Unfortunately, this pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} limit is out of range for ATLAS and CMS, while for LHCb it is still too low to collect enough statistics.

A few estimations of the production cross-section at the threshold, σ​(p​p→T4​c)𝜎→𝑝𝑝subscript𝑇4𝑐\sigma(pp\to T_{4c}), were made in Carvalho et al. (2016); Abreu et al. (2023); Becchi (2022). The problem with the production calculations at threshold is that the tetraquark is produced without a transverse momentum, making it difficult to observe at the LHC. Indeed, the 𝒪​(αs4)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠4{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{4}) scattering process produces a tetraquark with zero transverse momentum (σ2→1∼δ​(pT)similar-tosubscript𝜎→21𝛿subscript𝑝𝑇\sigma_{2\to 1}\sim\delta(p_{T})), as required by momentum conservation. This means that, unless one introduces the nonzero transverse momentum component in the initial state partons in an effective way (consider, for example, the ISR simulation or the kTsubscript𝑘𝑇k_{T}-factorization scheme), one has to study the inclusive production process.

To date, only one theoretical calculation of T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} inclusive hadronic cross-section has been made Feng et al. (2023); this calculation is based on NRQCD at the lowest order in v𝑣v (velocity) expansion. Unfortunately, it will be challenging to compare their results with the future experimental data, as they did not account for the experimental cuts in the calculation of the hadronic cross-section. For this reason, the goal of the present article is to obtain the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} cross-sections that can be compared in the future with the cross-sections at the LHC experiments.

Now, we develop the production formalism for an S𝑆S-wave fully heavy tetraquark based on a factorization scheme which employes the tetraquark four-body wave function. We present the calculation of the σ​(p​p→T4​c+X)𝜎→𝑝𝑝subscript𝑇4𝑐𝑋\sigma(pp\to T_{4c}+X) cross-section at the 𝒪​(αs5)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠5{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{5}) order within the Color Singlet Model (CSM) by means of a projection technique different from the one employed in Feng et al. (2023). The authors of Feng et al. (2023) apply the amplitude projection onto the diquark-antidiquark cluster, |c​c⟩⊗|c¯​c¯⟩tensor-productket𝑐𝑐ket¯𝑐¯𝑐|cc\rangle\otimes|\bar{c}\bar{c}\rangle, with the help of covariant projectors derived previously in Feng et al. (2022). 111The authors of Refs. Feng et al. (2023, 2022) apply in Feng et al. (2023) the projectors in the diquark-antidiquark basis proposed earlier in Feng et al. (2022). In our opinion, this projection technique was only partially explained in Feng et al. (2022), and no further details were provided in Feng et al. (2023). Indeed, we tried to reproduce the results of Feng et al. (2023), but failed because we could not find the recipe for the implementation of the projectors of Eq. (10) of Ref. Feng et al. (2022). Therefore, it might be helpful if the authors of Feng et al. (2022, 2023) could provide more details on the derivation and implementation of their projection technique in the diquark-antidiquark basis. By contrast, we perform the amplitude projection onto the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} in the |c​c¯⟩⊗|c​c¯⟩tensor-productket𝑐¯𝑐ket𝑐¯𝑐|c\bar{c}\rangle\otimes|c\bar{c}\rangle basis, for which the spin-color projection techniques are well established Guberina et al. (1980); Kuhn et al. (1979). With this approach, a production amplitude of the diquark-antidiquark cluster forming T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} can be decomposed into the sum of a few amplitudes in the meson-like basis. This technique of basis transformation was proposed in Refs. Becchi et al. (2020a, b), in which the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} and T4​bsubscript𝑇4𝑏T_{4b} partial decay widths were estimated. Concerning the production formalism, the use of the covariant projectors onto the |c​c¯⟩ket𝑐¯𝑐|c\bar{c}\rangle-states, which are widely applied to the study of quarkonium production, validates the reliability of our results and greatly reduces the computational cost. In our calculation, the IR divergencies are regularized with a pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} cut-off, analogous to the IR regularization of the SPS NLO∗ contribution to σ​(p​p→J/ψ​J/ψ+X)𝜎→𝑝𝑝𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓𝑋\sigma(pp\to J/\psi\,J/\psi+X) performed in Lansberg and Shao (2015); Likhoded et al. (2016).

We emphasize that we carry out an accurate pQCD calculation of the production matrix elements without utilizing any of the multipurpose Monte Carlo event generators developed in the high-energy physics community. It is worth noting that our formalism can be applied in the future also to the b​b​b¯​b¯𝑏𝑏¯𝑏¯𝑏bb\bar{b}\bar{b} and b​c​b¯​c¯𝑏𝑐¯𝑏¯𝑐bc\bar{b}\bar{c} tetraquarks.

The article is organized as follows. In Section II, we present the formalism of T4​c​(0++,1+−,2++)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript0absentsuperscript1absentsuperscript2absentT_{4c}\left(0^{++},1^{+-},2^{++}\right) production: we construct the production amplitudes in the meson-like basis with the relativistic degrees of freedom totally integrated out. In Section III, we apply this formalism to the g​g→c​c¯​c​c¯​g→𝑔𝑔𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐𝑔gg\to c\bar{c}c\bar{c}g scattering process, calculate the gauge invariant matrix elements for the T4​c+gsubscript𝑇4𝑐𝑔T_{4c}+g final state and discuss the impact of the ISR contribution. In Section IV, we present the hadronic cross-sections in the kinematic ranges relevant to the ongoing experiments at LHC. In Section V, we estimate the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} yields in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum at LHCb and we derive constraints to discriminate among the possible T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} candidates for X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900). In Section VI, we figure out which di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi structures can be interpreted as genuine resonances of the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} family. In Section VII, we report our results.

II Phenomenology of T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} production

In the collinear approach, the leading-order process of the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} production with experimentally observable transverse momentum necessarily implies the 2→2→222\to 2 scattering process, which occurs at the 𝒪​(αs5)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠5{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{5}) order. Moreover, in the LHC energy range, the gluon-gluon luminosity density dominates over the quark-gluon and quark-antiquark one. In the dominant gluon-gluon channel one needs to consider a process with at least one real gluon in the final state:

g​(k1)​g​(k2)→T4​c​(P)+g​(k3),→𝑔subscript𝑘1𝑔subscript𝑘2subscript𝑇4𝑐𝑃𝑔subscript𝑘3g(k_{1})\,g(k_{2})\to T_{4c}(P)\,+\,g(k_{3})\,, (1)

where a final state hard gluon recoils against the heavy resonance T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c}, thus leading to a measurable transverse momentum.

For tetraquark production, we adopt the CSM, which was originally employed for charmonium production. In this model the c​c¯𝑐¯𝑐c\bar{c}-pair is projected onto the color-singlet Fock state, and the quantum numbers of the c​c¯𝑐¯𝑐c\bar{c}-pair do not evolve between the production of the heavy-quark pair and its formation into the bound state. The only difference in the case of a fully charmed c​c¯​c​c¯𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐c\bar{c}c\bar{c} tetraquark is that now each c​c¯𝑐¯𝑐c\bar{c}-pair is projected onto |c​c¯⟩ket𝑐¯𝑐|c\bar{c}\rangle-configuration with a particular spin and color. As we will show later, the two projected |c​c¯⟩ket𝑐¯𝑐|c\bar{c}\rangle-configurations are coupled to a color-singlet |c​c⟩⊗|c¯​c¯⟩tensor-productket𝑐𝑐ket¯𝑐¯𝑐|cc\rangle\otimes|\bar{c}\bar{c}\rangle configuration with the spin of T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c}. In the rest of the text, we mean CSM by default.

In this approximation, the production amplitude reduces to the product of the wave function at the origin and the scattering matrix element projected onto the |c​c¯​c​c¯⟩ket𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐|c\bar{c}c\bar{c}\rangle Fock state with a given spin J𝐽J. The approximation of neglecting the relative motion used in Eq. (3) also allows one to move safely from the diquark-antidiquark basis to the meson-like basis in the calculation of ℳ​(g​g→[c​c¯​c​c¯]​(J)+g)ℳ→𝑔𝑔delimited-[]𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐𝐽𝑔{\cal M}\left(gg\to\left[c\bar{c}c\bar{c}\right](J)+g\right). As long as the relative motion is neglected, the total amplitude is insensitive to the dynamics of heavy quarks in the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} rest frame. This means that the production amplitudes calculated with the factorization given by the right-hand side of Eq. (3) are independent of the choice of the basis for building the |c​c¯​c​c¯⟩ket𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐|c\bar{c}c\bar{c}\rangle Fock states.

The relations between the diquark-antidiquark basis and the meson-like basis have been discussed in previous studies Becchi et al. (2020a, b). The Fierz transformations of Eqs. (4)—(7) are unitary transformations in spin and color space, which convert the orthonormal ||cc⟩⊗|c¯c¯⟩⟩\left||cc\rangle\otimes|\bar{c}\bar{c}\rangle\right\rangle states to the orthonormal ||cc¯⟩⊗|cc¯⟩⟩\left||c\bar{c}\rangle\otimes|c\bar{c}\rangle\right\rangle states. In practice, these transformations act on the spinor structure of the ℳ​(g​g→[c​c¯​c​c¯]​(J)+g)ℳ→𝑔𝑔delimited-[]𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐𝐽𝑔{\cal M}\left(gg\to\left[c\bar{c}c\bar{c}\right](J)+g\right) matrix elements. Since the initial state is a diquark-antidiquark configuration, the unpolarized cross-section calculations require summing over the spinor polarizations in the diquark-antidiquark basis. However with the help of these transformations  (4)—(7), this sum can be calculated in a more efficient way in the meson-like basis, for which the projection technique is well-established Guberina et al. (1980); Kuhn et al. (1979).

III Perturbative calculation

In the factorization scheme of Eq. (3) we construct the matrix elements with the selected ||cc¯⟩⊗|cc¯⟩⟩1\left||c\bar{c}\rangle\otimes|c\bar{c}\rangle\right\rangle_{1} states, starting from the matrix elements with two heavy quark-antiquark pairs generated with 𝐪𝟏=𝐪𝟐=𝐪𝟏𝟐=0subscript𝐪1subscript𝐪2subscript𝐪120{\bf q_{1}}={\bf q_{2}}={\bf q_{12}}=0. In these perturbative calculations, we work with the 𝒪​(gs5)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑔𝑠5{\cal O}(g_{s}^{5}) matrix elements for the g​g→c​c¯​c​c¯​g→𝑔𝑔𝑐¯𝑐𝑐¯𝑐𝑔gg\to c\bar{c}c\bar{c}g partonic-level process, where all gluons, quarks and antiquarks are defined on the mass shell. We generate the full set of 682 tree matrix elements in Feynman gauge by means of the FeynArts Hahn (2001) package. Figure 1 shows a diagrammatic sketch of the process.

Each matrix element contains a product of the two fermion lines due to the two quark-antiquark pairs

This technique allows one to handle the spinors in the code analytically in a covariant way. The projection was carried out with our code in the framework of the FeynCalc Shtabovenko et al. (2020) package. Further evaluation of the matrix elements containing traces was performed in FORM Kuipers et al. (2013) computer algebra system. The implementation of the projection technique in our code was verified by reproducing the g​g→J/ψ​J/ψ→𝑔𝑔𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓gg\to J/\psi\,J/\psi analytic cross-section from Humpert and Mery (1983).

After introducing the spinor polarization sums, it is convenient to address the phase space factor Iph.sp.subscript𝐼ph.sp.I_{\textrm{ph.sp.}} in Eq. (3). For the phase space integration, one needs to be sure that the normalizations of the matrix element squared, wave function squared and invariant phase space measure are consistent with one another. It must be remembered that the polarization sums are written for spinors with the relativistic normalization u¯​u=2​mc¯𝑢𝑢2subscript𝑚𝑐\bar{u}u=2m_{c}, and the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} wave function satisfies the nonrelativistic normalization. One then needs to compensate only for the spinor normalization by a factor IQ​Qsubscript𝐼𝑄𝑄I_{QQ} for each pair 222It is fairly common to absorb IQ​Qsubscript𝐼𝑄𝑄I_{QQ} into the projectors definition, but here we prefer to give it in a factorized form. and to compensate for the relativistic phase space by a factor I4​Qsubscript𝐼4𝑄I_{4Q}, such that the total correction factor in the four-quark center-of-mass frame is

Iph.sp.=I4​Q×IQ​Q×IQ​Q=4​2​M−3/2,subscript𝐼ph.sp.subscript𝐼4𝑄subscript𝐼𝑄𝑄subscript𝐼𝑄𝑄42superscript𝑀32I_{\textrm{ph.sp.}}=I_{4Q}\times I_{QQ}\times I_{QQ}=4\sqrt{2}\,M^{-3/2}, (23)

where I4​Q=2​Msubscript𝐼4𝑄2𝑀I_{4Q}=\sqrt{2M} and IQ​Q=1/mQ​Q=2/Msubscript𝐼𝑄𝑄1subscript𝑚𝑄𝑄2𝑀I_{QQ}=1/m_{QQ}=2/M.

Now let us address the diagrams that represent the g​g→T4​c+g→𝑔𝑔subscript𝑇4𝑐𝑔gg\to T_{4c}+g scattering matrix elements. The full set of diagrams can be regarded as the set of three groups: initial state radiation (ISR), where a gluon is emitted from an incoming gluon line, final state radiation (FSR), where a gluon is emitted from an outgoing quark line; and what we call the rest (Rest), where a gluon is emitted from an internal line (either a quark or a gluon line) or a four-gluon vertex. As an example, in Fig. 1 we display two ISR diagrams (a,b), two FSR diagrams (c,d), and one Rest diagram (e). We remark that the diagrams with a four-gluon vertex occur in each of the three groups.

The abovementioned groups contribute differently to C𝐶C-even and C𝐶C-odd tetraquark production. For example, the ISR group (144 diagrams) contributes only to the amplitudes with a C𝐶C-even tetraquark in the final state. This can be explained by C𝐶C-parity conservation in the g​g→|c​c​c¯​c¯​(JP​C)⟩1→𝑔𝑔subscriptket𝑐𝑐¯𝑐¯𝑐superscript𝐽𝑃𝐶1gg\to|cc\bar{c}\bar{c}(J^{PC})\rangle_{1} reaction, which prohibits the production of T4​c​(1+−)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript1absentT_{4c}(1^{+-}) at threshold in the gluon fusion channel. We checked that this prohibition remains valid when one of the two gluons goes off-shell, which is exactly what occurs in the ISR process.

Another type of selection rule concerns the case of two-trace projection onto the color-singlet |c​c¯⟩ket𝑐¯𝑐|c\bar{c}\rangle structures. If C𝐶C-parity is conserved in the g(∗)​…​g(∗)→|c​c¯⟩1→superscript𝑔…superscript𝑔subscriptket𝑐¯𝑐1g^{(*)}\ldots g^{(*)}\to|c\bar{c}\rangle_{1} reaction, with the gluons allowed to be off-shell, then a nonzero contribution can arise only from the diagrams in which any fermion line associated with a vector |c​c¯⟩1subscriptket𝑐¯𝑐1|c\bar{c}\rangle_{1} structure is coupled to an odd number of gluons (three), whereas any fermion line associated with a pseudoscalar |c​c¯⟩1subscriptket𝑐¯𝑐1|c\bar{c}\rangle_{1} structure is coupled to an even number of gluons (two or four). According to our calculations, this selection rule proves to be valid, i.e. for the production process studied, C𝐶C-parity is indeed conserved in the abovementioned reaction. At the same time, as expected, we saw that this selection rule does not hold in the g(∗)​…​g(∗)→|c​c¯⟩8→superscript𝑔…superscript𝑔subscriptket𝑐¯𝑐8g^{(*)}\ldots g^{(*)}\to|c\bar{c}\rangle_{8} reaction.

As a result of our calculations, we ascertain that the matrix elements for the C𝐶C-even tetraquarks with JP​C={0++,2++}superscript𝐽𝑃𝐶superscript0absentsuperscript2absentJ^{PC}=\{0^{++},2^{++}\} are proportional to the fully anti-symmetric color structure fA​B​Csubscript𝑓𝐴𝐵𝐶f_{ABC}. Conversely, the matrix elements for the JP​C=1+−superscript𝐽𝑃𝐶superscript1absentJ^{PC}=1^{+-} tetraquark contain both the fully symmetric and fully anti-symmetric color structures dA​B​Csubscript𝑑𝐴𝐵𝐶d_{ABC} and fA​B​Csubscript𝑓𝐴𝐵𝐶f_{ABC}, however only the part that is proportional to dA​B​Csubscript𝑑𝐴𝐵𝐶d_{ABC} survives in the squared matrix element. In other words, we found a correlation between the color structure and the C𝐶C-parity of the T4​c+gsubscript𝑇4𝑐𝑔T_{4c}+g final state: fA​B​Csubscript𝑓𝐴𝐵𝐶f_{ABC} in the case of negative final state C𝐶C-parity, and dA​B​Csubscript𝑑𝐴𝐵𝐶d_{ABC} in the case of positive final state C𝐶C-parity. It is worth recalling that the same correlation between the final state C𝐶C-parity and color structure has been found in the background process of gluon fusion to double charmonia with a real gluon emission Likhoded et al. (2016).

After splitting the full set of diagrams into ISR, FSR and Rest groups in the code, we managed to ascertain that only the ISR diagrams generate a divergence in the total amplitude. Whereas the contribution of the FSR+Rest groups alone is IR safe, the ISR contribution is responsible for a divergent behavior in the soft and collinear limits. 333One can disentangle the IR divergences by splitting the phase space into three regions that lead to the following three contributions to the total cross-section: (1) finite cross-section, (2) cross-section in the soft (s→1→𝑠1s\to 1) and soft-collinear (s→1→𝑠1s\to 1 and either t→0→𝑡0t\to 0 or u→0→𝑢0u\to 0) limits and (3) the cross-section in the hard-collinear (t→0→𝑡0t\to 0 or u→0→𝑢0u\to 0) limit. The soft and soft-collinear limits correspond to the production at threshold, σ2→1∼δ​(pT)similar-tosubscript𝜎→21𝛿subscript𝑝𝑇\sigma_{2\to 1}\sim\delta(p_{T}). Since in this article we consider a real gluon emission, we are not interested in the soft limit and we address only the correction for the hard-collinear limit. As mentioned earlier, the ISR contribution vanishes in the case of 1+−superscript1absent1^{+-} tetraquark production. Therefore, we find the F(1)​(s,t)superscript𝐹1𝑠𝑡F^{(1)}(s,t) expression to be finite in the t→(1−s)→𝑡1𝑠t\to(1-s) and t→0→𝑡0t\to 0 limits. Meanwhile, the F(0)​(s,t)superscript𝐹0𝑠𝑡F^{(0)}(s,t) and F(2)​(s,t)superscript𝐹2𝑠𝑡F^{(2)}(s,t) expressions diverge due to the t​(1−s−t)𝑡1𝑠𝑡t\,(1-s-t) factor in their denominators. Thus, σ^​(g​g→T4​c​(1+−)+g)^𝜎→𝑔𝑔subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript1absent𝑔\widehat{\sigma}(gg\to T_{4c}(1^{+-})+g) is the only partonic cross-section which is collinear stable by default. The collinear stable expressions for σ^​(g​g→T4​c​(0++)+g)^𝜎→𝑔𝑔subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript0absent𝑔\widehat{\sigma}(gg\to T_{4c}(0^{++})+g) and σ^​(g​g→T4​c​(2++)+g)^𝜎→𝑔𝑔subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absent𝑔\widehat{\sigma}(gg\to T_{4c}(2^{++})+g) can be obtained by considering an evolution of the parton distribution functions (PDFs) via the DGLAP equations. With this technique the 1/εIR1subscript𝜀IR1/\varepsilon_{\textrm{IR}} poles, having been isolated after performing the phase space integration with dimensional regularization, can be absorbed into the evolving PDFs.

In this article, we propose a simpler solution: applying a pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} cut-off consistent with an experimental low pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} cut. Hence, we expect that, starting from some value in the transverse momentum, our calculated cross-sections reproduce the cross-sections with the correct behavior in the low pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} limit. Our choices of pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} cuts for the LHC experiments are discussed in Subsection IV.1.

IV cross-sections in the kinematic regions of interest for the LHC experiments

IV.1 Kinematic regions

So far, observations of T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} candidates have been made in the J/ψ(→μ+μ−)J/ψ(→μ+μ−)J/\psi\left(\to\mu^{+}\mu^{-}\right)J/\psi\left(\to\mu^{+}\mu^{-}\right) and J/ψ(→μ+μ−)ψ(2S)(→μ+μ−)J/\psi\left(\to\mu^{+}\mu^{-}\right)\psi(2S)\left(\to\mu^{+}\mu^{-}\right) decay modes. However, in the experimental articles, the cuts are often reported for individual muons or di-muons, rather than for the entire di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi system (hereafter, we refer to the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mode, but the same applies to the J/ψ​ψ​(2​S)𝐽𝜓𝜓2𝑆J/\psi\,\psi(2S) mode in the case of ATLAS). In the LHCb article Aaij et al. (2020), it is explicitly stated that, in the pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T}-threshold approach, the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi candidates were selected with the requirement pTdi-​J/ψ>5.2​GeVsuperscriptsubscript𝑝𝑇di-𝐽𝜓5.2GeVp_{T}^{\text{di-}J/\psi}>5.2~{}\text{GeV}. By contrast, ATLAS and CMS experiments report only selection cuts on pT​(μ)subscript𝑝𝑇𝜇p_{T}(\mu) or pT​(μ+​μ−)subscript𝑝𝑇superscript𝜇superscript𝜇p_{T}(\mu^{+}\mu^{-}) in Aad et al. (2023); Hayrapetyan et al. (2024). In ATLAS, two of the four selected muons must have pT>4​GeVsubscript𝑝𝑇4GeVp_{T}>4~{}\text{GeV}, and the remaining two must have pT>3​GeVsubscript𝑝𝑇3GeVp_{T}>3~{}\text{GeV}. In CMS, the low pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} cut on each of the di-muons is pT​(μ+​μ−)>3.5​GeVsubscript𝑝𝑇superscript𝜇superscript𝜇3.5GeVp_{T}(\mu^{+}\mu^{-})>3.5~{}\text{GeV}. Each experiment specifies an acceptance range in terms of the pseudorapidity of individual muons: |η​(μ)|<2.5𝜂𝜇2.5|\eta(\mu)|<2.5 in ATLAS; |η​(μ)|<2.4𝜂𝜇2.4|\eta(\mu)|<2.4 in CMS, and 2<η​(μ)<52𝜂𝜇52<\eta(\mu)<5 in LHCb. Meanwhile, none of the experiments applies the cuts on the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi pseudorapidity.

Since our code is designed solely for the production process, we do not track the subsequent decay of the produced tetraquark and we are therefore unable to impose cuts on its decay products. Therefore, we impose cuts on the phase space volume expressed in the tetraquark’s transverse momentum pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} and rapidity y𝑦y variables. We consider prompt production in the three kinematic regions of interest for the LHC experiments: the forward kinematic region 2<y<5,5<pT​(GeV)<50formulae-sequence2𝑦55subscript𝑝𝑇GeV502<y<5,\quad 5<p_{T}(\text{GeV})<50 and the central kinematic region, |y|<2𝑦2|y|<2, with the two pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} ranges, 10<pT​(GeV)<10010subscript𝑝𝑇GeV10010<p_{T}(\text{GeV})<100 and 20<pT​(GeV)<10020subscript𝑝𝑇GeV10020<p_{T}(\text{GeV})<100. In the case of the forward kinematic region, we assume that our cuts approximately correspond to the LHCb ones. The cases of ATLAS and CMS are more complicated since there are, as yet, no measurements with given fiducial cuts on the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi transverse momentum and pseudorapidity. Even though the signal events can be collected at lower pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T}, i.e.formulae-sequence𝑖𝑒i.e. even below 7 GeV for CMS and 14 GeV for ATLAS, we recognize that the efficiency is poorly defined near these thresholds. For this reason, we prefer to use more conservative pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} ranges that are accessible to ATLAS and CMS not only for the yield measurements but also for the cross-section measurements. In the future, we can readily reproduce our calculations and refine the results according to the known fiducial cuts in terms of pTdi-​J/ψsuperscriptsubscript𝑝𝑇di-𝐽𝜓p_{T}^{\text{di-}J/\psi} and ydi-​J/ψsuperscript𝑦di-𝐽𝜓y^{\text{di-}J/\psi} variables.

IV.2 Hadronic cross-sections

We calculate the hadronic cross-sections in the framework of the collinear factorization of the initial partons. As mentioned earlier, the partonic cross-section in the gluon-gluon fusion channel, convoluted with the gluon density functions G​(x1,2,μ)𝐺subscript𝑥12𝜇G(x_{1,2},\mu), constitutes the dominant part of the cross-section at LHC. For the numerical computations, we make use of the Monte Carlo integration coded with a C++ macro linked to the ROOT Brun and Rademakers (1997) environment. Since we deal with a two-body phase space, we find it more convenient to use private code rather than applying built-in algorithms for the phase space integration. The proton-proton cross-section reads

We do not separate the renormalization scale in αs​(μ)subscript𝛼𝑠𝜇\alpha_{s}(\mu) and the factorization scale in G​(x1,2,μ)𝐺subscript𝑥12𝜇G(x_{1,2},\mu). For the scale range, we follow the conventional choice ET/2≤μ≤2​ETsubscript𝐸𝑇2𝜇2subscript𝐸𝑇E_{T}/2\leq\mu\leq 2E_{T}, with ET=pT2+M2subscript𝐸𝑇superscriptsubscript𝑝𝑇2superscript𝑀2E_{T}=\sqrt{p_{T}^{2}+M^{2}} being the transverse energy.

The spectroscopy inputs, namely the masses, the four-body wave functions at the origin, and the mixing parameter of the color configurations in 0(′)⁣++superscript0′absent0^{(\prime)++} states, are drawn from the nonrelativistic quark model calculations Wang et al. (2021) and Lü et al. (2020). In Appendix A, we list the spectroscopy inputs for 1​S1𝑆1S, 2​S2𝑆2S and 3​S3𝑆3S states of the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} tetraquark with quantum numbers JP​C={0++,1+−,2++}superscript𝐽𝑃𝐶superscript0absentsuperscript1absentsuperscript2absentJ^{PC}=\{0^{++},1^{+-},2^{++}\}. In Appendix A we also include the root mean square radii used to extract the wave functions at the origin.

In the CSM, the JP​Csuperscript𝐽𝑃𝐶J^{PC} dependence of the cross-section distribution shapes comes from the short-distance factor, whereas the wave function magnitude affects only the normalization. Note also that, for each JP​Csuperscript𝐽𝑃𝐶J^{PC}, the obtained expression of the short-distance factor F(J)superscript𝐹𝐽F^{(J)} holds for any radial excitation n​S𝑛𝑆nS. Therefore, it is reasonable to factor out a radial state-dependent dimensionless factor Φ(J)​(n​S)superscriptΦ𝐽𝑛𝑆\Phi^{(J)}(nS) as follows

σ=Φ​(n​S)​σ¯​(μ,⟨M⟩,⟨α2⟩),Φ​(n​S)=1010​ϕ​(n​S)​(as given in Appendix A),formulae-sequence𝜎Φ𝑛𝑆¯𝜎𝜇delimited-⟨⟩𝑀delimited-⟨⟩superscript𝛼2Φ𝑛𝑆superscript1010italic-ϕ𝑛𝑆as given in Appendix A\displaystyle\sigma=\Phi(nS)\>\overline{\sigma}(\mu,\langle M\rangle,\langle\alpha^{2}\rangle),\qquad\qquad\Phi(nS)=10^{10}\phi(nS)~{}~{}(\textrm{as given in Appendix~{}\ref{app:spectr_inputs}}), (38)

where the J𝐽J notation is omitted, ϕitalic-ϕ\phi is the reduced wave function introduced in Eq. (33), and ⟨M⟩delimited-⟨⟩𝑀\langle M\rangle and ⟨α2⟩delimited-⟨⟩superscript𝛼2\langle\alpha^{2}\rangle are the mean values of M𝑀M and α2superscript𝛼2\alpha^{2} obtained from averaging over the radial state masses. As we discuss later in the text, the impact of varying the M𝑀M and α2superscript𝛼2\alpha^{2} numerical inputs is small compared to the scale uncertainty. In Eq. (38) we refer to σ𝜎\sigma and σ¯¯𝜎\overline{\sigma} as the full and reduced cross-sections, respectively.

The reduced cross-section σ¯¯𝜎\overline{\sigma} represents the universal result of the pQCD calculation, which can be matched to the tetraquark wave functions obtained by solving the four-body problem in any model. As yet, there is no solid understanding of how to assign the quantum numbers to the experimentally observed states. The experimentally observed states might not be the ground states, but the radial excitations with higher predicted masses or the superpositions of two or more unresolved neighboring states. Moreover, for some states, the four-body wave functions, predicted, for example, in Wang et al. (2021) and in Lü et al. (2020), differ by an order of magnitude (see Appendix A). For these reasons, we prefer to present the cross-sections in the form of the reduced cross-sections σ¯¯𝜎\overline{\sigma}.

In the full cross-section σ𝜎\sigma there are two main sources of uncertainties: the uncertainty in the wave function magnitude and the uncertainty in the scale definition. Their separation in Eq. (38) does take place, since the σ¯¯𝜎\overline{\sigma} dependence on M𝑀M and α2superscript𝛼2\alpha^{2} is small compared to the dependence on scale μ𝜇\mu (at least at the leading-order accuracy). (2023); Hayrapetyan et al. (2024) results in at most a 10% deviation in σ¯​(⟨M⟩)¯𝜎delimited-⟨⟩𝑀\overline{\sigma}(\langle M\rangle) calculated with the average over all the measured masses, ⟨M⟩≃6900similar-to-or-equalsdelimited-⟨⟩𝑀6900\langle M\rangle\simeq 6900 MeV. V Comparison with the signal yields in the J/ψ​J/ψ𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓J/\psi\,J/\psi spectrum

The total yield of di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi events measurable in the experiment includes a direct production component, a feed-down component (in which at least one J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi originates from ψ​(2​S)𝜓2𝑆\psi(2S), χc​(1​P)subscript𝜒𝑐1𝑃\chi_{c}(1P) or other higher charmonium states), a resonant component, attributed to an exotic fully charmed state, and a small rate of non-prompt events from b𝑏b-hadron decays. It should be observed that the prompt nonresonant di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi yields (direct and feed-down) are given by the sum of the contributions of the SPS and DPS production mechanisms. By contrast, the resonant production is exclusively associated with the SPS mechanism.

Assuming that the resonantly produced J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi-pairs originate from a T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} tetraquark, we can pin down a few possible resonant contributions, which we refer to as the direct, the charmonium feed-down and the tetraquark feed-down contributions. The direct component corresponds to a T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} directly produced and directly decaying into the J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi-pair. It can be observed in the fully reconstructed decay, and its yield can be estimated as Ndirect(SPS)​(T4​c)⋅Br​(J/ψ​J/ψ)⋅superscriptsubscript𝑁direct(SPS)subscript𝑇4𝑐Br𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓N_{\textrm{direct}}^{\textrm{(SPS)}}(T_{4c})\cdot\textrm{Br}(J/\psi\,J/\psi). The charmonium feed-down component corresponds to a T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} directly produced and decaying into the J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi-pair via at least one intermediate higher charmonium state. As an example of the charmonium feed-down component, one might consider the T4​c→χc(→J/ψγ)χc(→J/ψγ)T_{4c}\to\chi_{c}(\to J/\psi\,\gamma)\>\chi_{c}(\to J/\psi\,\gamma) partially reconstructed decay chain, where the photons escape the reconstruction. The tetraquark feed-down component corresponds to a T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} that proceeds from a higher mass tetraquark decay and subsequently decays into the J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi-pair. As an example of the tetraquark feed-down component one might consider the T4​c(2S)→T4​c(1S)(→J/ψJ/ψ)π+π−T_{4c}(2S)\to T_{4c}(1S)(\to J/\psi\,J/\psi)\,\pi^{+}\pi^{-} decay chain.

In this subsection, we estimate only the yields of the main resonant component, Ndirect(SPS)​(T4​c)⋅Br​(J/ψ​J/ψ)⋅superscriptsubscript𝑁direct(SPS)subscript𝑇4𝑐Br𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓N_{\textrm{direct}}^{\textrm{(SPS)}}(T_{4c})\cdot\textrm{Br}(J/\psi\,J/\psi), in order to draw some conclusions from its comparison with the measured yields. In that respect, let us review the available data on the signal yields in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi spectrum. First, in all three researches Aaij et al. (2020); Aad et al. (2023); Hayrapetyan et al. (2024) the narrow peak around 6900 MeV has been observed. Alongside the clear peak near 6900 MeV a relatively broad structure, starting from 6200​MeV6200MeV6200~{}\text{MeV} (the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi threshold), and a narrow structure at a higher invariant mass around 7300 MeV have been seen Aaij et al. (2020); Aad et al. (2023); Hayrapetyan et al. (2024). While the shape of the first broad structure in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum appears consistent across all three studies, and it certainly indicates the presence of the experimental excess over the background, the yield of the third structure is suppressed and differs across the three experiments. In the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum measured by LHCb Aaij et al. (2020), the small bump seen just below 7300 MeV was neglected because of the low statistical significance. No evidence of this structure was found later by ATLAS Aad et al. (2023). In the recently published CMS study Hayrapetyan et al. (2024) this structure was confirmed at 7287 MeV with a statistical significance of 4.7​σ4.7𝜎4.7\,\sigma.

Concerning the first broad structure, the statistical significance in all three experiments exceeds 5.0​σ5.0𝜎5.0\,\sigma. In the CMS study Hayrapetyan et al. (2024) this broad structure was resolved into a single peak and an additional component, this latter being responsible for the threshold enhancement just above 6200 MeV due to the opening of the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi threshold. This additional component was incorporated into the background fit by introducing a separate Breight-Wigner function. By contrast with CMS, in the LHCb study Aaij et al. (2020) the full broad structure in the mass region 6200÷6700​MeV62006700MeV6200\div 6700~{}\text{MeV} was treated as a threshold enhancement. The yield enhancement in this region was fitted with two Breight-Wigner functions, called “Threshold BW1” and “Threshold BW2” components in Aaij et al. (2020). Although these two Breight-Wigners could fit the overlap between the threshold enhancement and a possible genuine resonant state, the broad structure was not interpreted as incorporating a true resonance. For this reason, no yield of the first broad structure was published by LHCb in Aaij et al. (2020). In the ATLAS study Aad et al. (2023) the first broad structure was fitted with two interfering Breight-Wigner functions. This interference hinted at the possibility that the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum in the region 6200÷6700​MeV62006700MeV6200\div 6700~{}\text{MeV} might have a more complex structure, comprising two coherently produced states with the same quantum numbers. It is important to add that, in ATLAS, the feed-down events — the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi events with one of the J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi coming from the ψ​(2​S)𝜓2𝑆\psi(2S) cascade decays — were included as an additional background. This charmonium feed-down contribution alters the background shape in the region of the first broad structure and, particularly, results in a small bump just above the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi threshold; this could be one of the explanations for the threshold enhancement seen in all three experiments.

Before making comparisons with the measured yields, it is important to point out some details in fitting the mass spectrum in Aaij et al. (2020); Aad et al. (2023); Hayrapetyan et al. (2024). Both the non-interfering and interfering scenarios were considered. On investigating the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum, LHCb and ATLAS also applied fitting models that allowed for the interference between the SPS component of the background and a Breight-Wigner for the threshold enhancement. While in the experimental analysis such a model is able to improve the quality of fit, it rejects the hypothesis that the first broad structure might include a genuine resonance. 444 This type of interference was considered to achieve a better agreement with data in the region of the dip between the first broad structure and the peak around 690069006900 MeV. We suggest that the SPS component of the background (as well as the DPS one) represents an uncoherent production of di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi pairs in different configurations with various JP​Csuperscript𝐽𝑃𝐶J^{PC}. In our opinion, this component can not interfere with the genuine resonant state characterized by unique JP​Csuperscript𝐽𝑃𝐶J^{PC}. On interpreting these fitting models, only the peak around 6900 MeV can be considered the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} resonance, and the entire first broad structure should be related to the background. In the CMS study Hayrapetyan et al. (2024) the models taking into account the interference with the background did not improve the fit quality. Thus, CMS applied a different fitting model, one in which all three observed resonances interfere with each other. Incorporating these interference terms showed a significant improvement in the regions of the dips between the resonances. We note that this fitting model unavoidably requires all three peaks to be assigned to the same JP​Csuperscript𝐽𝑃𝐶J^{PC} quantum numbers.

It should be mentioned that the amount of data on the measured yields is rather poor. ATLAS did not report any signal yields Aad et al. (2023), and CMS reported only the signal yields measured within the “no interference” fitting model Hayrapetyan et al. (2024):

It is important to stress the consistency in the orders of magnitude among the three independently predicted quantities: the pQCD cross-sections calculated in this article, the four-body wave functions from the nonrelativistic quark models Wang et al. (2024)). As a result, the branching ratios calculated in Sang et al. (2024); Wang and Yang (2024); Agaev et al. (2023), Br​(T4​c→J/ψ​J/ψ)≈(0.5÷1)Br→subscript𝑇4𝑐𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓0.51\text{Br}(T_{4c}\to J/\psi\,J/\psi)\approx(0.5\div 1), lead to a three-order-of-magnitude discrepancy. By contrast, the good order of magnitude agreement for the values of Eq. (48) hints that di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi decay mode is suppressed Becchi et al. (2020a).

VI.2 Interpretation of the remaining two di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi structures

In addition to the outlined interpretation of the X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) state, the remaining two structures in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi spectrum should be addressed. The yields of the first two peaks observed by CMS are approximately in a 1:1:111:1 ratio. As discussed earlier, we expect the 2++superscript2absent2^{++} dominance in the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} visibility factors because the combined 2++superscript2absent2^{++} enhancement factor in production and decay is much larger than the corresponding suppression factor in the wave function. This finding disproves the hypothesis of the N​(0++):N​(2++)≈1:1:𝑁superscript0absent𝑁superscript2absent1:1N(0^{++}):N(2^{++})\approx 1:1 ratio for the first two peaks observed by CMS. The spectroscopy models Wang et al. (2021); Lü et al. (2020) do not predict the ratio Φ(2)​(1​S):Φ(2)​(2​S):superscriptΦ21𝑆superscriptΦ22𝑆\Phi^{(2)}(1S):\Phi^{(2)}(2S) to be close to 1:1:111:1, which could otherwise explain the first two peaks as the 2++​(1​S)superscript2absent1𝑆2^{++}(1S) and 2++​(2​S)superscript2absent2𝑆2^{++}(2S) states. In our opinion, the hypothesis of the T4​c​(2++​(1​S)):T4​c​(2++​(2​S)):subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absent1𝑆subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absent2𝑆T_{4c}(2^{++}(1S)):T_{4c}(2^{++}(2S)) assignment deserves to be considered, but more precise studies of the four-body wave functions and the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi branching dependence on the radial state are needed in order to work out the constraints on the Φ(2)​(1​S)​Br​(1​S):Φ(2)​(2​S)​Br​(2​S):superscriptΦ21𝑆Br1𝑆superscriptΦ22𝑆Br2𝑆\Phi^{(2)}(1S)\>\text{Br}(1S):\Phi^{(2)}(2S)\>\text{Br}(2S) ratio.

Most likely, in LHCb and ATLAS, the broad structure in the mass region 6200÷6700​MeV62006700MeV6200\div 6700~{}\text{MeV} represents an overlap of the threshold enhancement contribution and one or more genuine resonance(s). Given the latest CMS results, where the interference with the background is unfavorable to the fitting model, the scenario in which the entire broad structure manifests as the threshold effect seems less significant. Besides the directly produced T4​c​(2++​(1​S))subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absent1𝑆T_{4c}(2^{++}(1S)) the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi broad structure might include several suppressed contributions. The subleading contributions are expected to come from the directly produced 0++​(1​S)superscript0absent1𝑆0^{++}(1S) tetraquark and from the 2++​(1​S)superscript2absent1𝑆2^{++}(1S) tetraquark produced through the feed-down from 2++​(2​S)superscript2absent2𝑆2^{++}(2S) in the T4​c​(2++)→T4​c​(2++)​{π0​π0,π+​π−}→subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absentsubscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absentsuperscript𝜋0superscript𝜋0superscript𝜋superscript𝜋T_{4c}(2^{++})\to T_{4c}(2^{++})\left\{\pi^{0}\pi^{0},\pi^{+}\pi^{-}\right\} hadronic mode. In both cases, we would assume a one-order-of-magnitude suppression in the visibility factor. In addition to the fully reconstructed T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} states, the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi broad structure contains contributions from the partially reconstructed T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} decay products that may impact the shape of the mass spectrum. For example, consider the T4​c​(2++)→J/ψ​ψ​(2​S)(→J/ψ​{π0​π0,π+​π−})→subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absentannotated𝐽𝜓𝜓2𝑆→absent𝐽𝜓superscript𝜋0superscript𝜋0superscript𝜋superscript𝜋T_{4c}(2^{++})\to J/\psi\>\psi(2S)(\to J/\psi\left\{\pi^{0}\pi^{0},\pi^{+}\pi^{-}\right\}) or T4​c(2++)→χc(→γJ/ψ)χc(→γJ/ψ)T_{4c}(2^{++})\to\chi_{c}(\to\gamma\,J/\psi)\>\chi_{c}(\to\gamma\,J/\psi) decay modes.

The enhancement in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum around 7300 MeV exceeds the predicted masses of the 3​S3𝑆3S radial excitations given in Table 4 by 250 MeV, making it challenging to attribute this peak (bump) to an S𝑆S-wave tetraquark. In Ref. Karliner and Rosner (2020) Karliner and Rosner observed that the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi invariant mass region between 6200 and 7300 MeV is rich in meson-meson and baryon-baryon thresholds that might be responsible for such a complex signal structure. As was observed, the dip around 6750​MeV6750MeV6750\,\mathrm{MeV} might correspond to the opening of the S𝑆S-wave di-χc​0subscript𝜒𝑐0\chi_{c0} channel at ≃6829similar-to-or-equalsabsent6829\simeq 6829 MeV, while the dip around 7200​MeV7200MeV7200\,\mathrm{MeV} could be correlated with the opening of the di-ηc​(2​S)subscript𝜂𝑐2𝑆\eta_{c}(2S) channel at ≃7276similar-to-or-equalsabsent7276\simeq 7276 MeV or Ξc​c​Ξ¯c​csubscriptΞ𝑐𝑐subscript¯Ξ𝑐𝑐\Xi_{cc}\bar{\Xi}_{cc} channel at ≃7244similar-to-or-equalsabsent7244\simeq 7244 MeV. Thus, the observation of the bump at 7300 MeV might only be induced by the opening of the di-ηc​(2​S)subscript𝜂𝑐2𝑆\eta_{c}(2S) or Ξc​c​Ξ¯c​csubscriptΞ𝑐𝑐subscript¯Ξ𝑐𝑐\Xi_{cc}\bar{\Xi}_{cc} channels. Combined information of both the four-body calculation mass predictions Wang et al. (2021); Lü et al. (2020) and exploration of the relevant thresholds in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi invariant mass Karliner and Rosner (2020), prompts us to avoid interpreting the third peak (bump) as a genuine tetraquark state.

VII conclusions

This article presents the factorization formalism for the production of an S𝑆S-wave fully heavy tetraquark in the SPS interaction. The formalism is based on the Fierz transformation, which allows one to construct the production amplitudes in the meson-like basis, for which the spin-color projection techniques are well established. The formalism outlined is applied to the calculation of T4​c​(0++,1+−,2++)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript0absentsuperscript1absentsuperscript2absentT_{4c}(0^{++},1^{+-},2^{++}) hadronic production cross-sections. The cross-sections are predicted in the kinematic regions accessible at the LHC experiments.

In the collinear approach, the leading-order process of T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} production with experimentally observable transverse momentum necessarily implies the 2→2→222\to 2 scattering process. Therefore, we calculate the inclusive σ​(p​p→T4​c+X)𝜎→𝑝𝑝subscript𝑇4𝑐𝑋\sigma(pp\to T_{4c}+X) cross-sections in the dominant channel of gluon fusion at the leading order, 𝒪​(αs5)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠5{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{5}). The 𝒪​(αs5)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠5{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{5}) short-distance factors are obtained from the pQCD calculations of the SPS matrix elements, projected onto all allowed T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} internal color and spin configurations compatible with the symmetry principles. The short-distance factors are further combined with the four-body T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} wave functions at the origin. The partonic cross-sections obtained are convoluted with the CTEQ18 gluon density functions and integrated over the (pT,η)subscript𝑝𝑇𝜂(p_{T},\eta) ranges accessible in the ATLAS, CMS and LHCb detectors.

We observe a few orders of magnitude suppression in the T4​c​(1+−)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript1absentT_{4c}(1^{+-}) production rate as well as dominance of the T4​c​(2++)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript2absentT_{4c}(2^{++}) production rate relative to that of T4​c​(0++)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript0absentT_{4c}(0^{++}). We predict the integral values and pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T}-distributions of the reduced cross-sections σ¯=σ/Φ¯𝜎𝜎Φ\overline{\sigma}=\sigma/\Phi, with the normalization given by the dimensionless factor Φ=1010​|Ψ​(0,0,0)|2/M9Φsuperscript1010superscriptΨ0002superscript𝑀9\Phi=10^{10}\,|\Psi(0,0,0)|^{2}/M^{9} derived from the four-body spectroscopy models (see Appendix A). In the large pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} limit, the differential distributions scale as d​σ¯​(0++,2++)/d​pT∼1/pT6similar-to𝑑¯𝜎superscript0absentsuperscript2absent𝑑subscript𝑝𝑇1superscriptsubscript𝑝𝑇6d\overline{\sigma}(0^{++},2^{++})/dp_{T}\sim 1/p_{T}^{6}  and  d​σ¯​(1+−)/d​pT∼1/pT8similar-to𝑑¯𝜎superscript1absent𝑑subscript𝑝𝑇1superscriptsubscript𝑝𝑇8d\overline{\sigma}(1^{+-})/dp_{T}\sim 1/p_{T}^{8}. The ratio r=σ¯​(2++)/σ¯​(0++)𝑟¯𝜎superscript2absent¯𝜎superscript0absentr=\overline{\sigma}(2^{++})/\overline{\sigma}(0^{++}) is found to be insensitive to the acceptance range, slightly increasing with pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} and reaching saturation in the large pTsubscript𝑝𝑇p_{T} limit. For the 5≤pT​(GeV)≤1005subscript𝑝𝑇GeV1005\leq p_{T}(\textrm{GeV})\leq 100 cut, the ratio lies in the 12≤r​(pT)≤1712𝑟subscript𝑝𝑇1712\leq r(p_{T})\leq 17 range.

Despite some differences in the fitting models, there is a clear consensus among ATLAS, CMS and LHCb regarding the existence of X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi invariant mass spectrum. Thanks to the fact that LHCb has published both the fiducial cuts on pTdi-​J/ψsuperscriptsubscript𝑝𝑇di-𝐽𝜓p_{T}^{\textrm{di-}J/\psi} and the experimental efficiency, we could compare the estimated number of pp→T4​c(→J/ψJ/ψ)+Xpp\to T_{4c}(\to J/\psi\,J/\psi)+X events with the X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900) signal yield at LHCb. Most important, we derive the following model-independent constraints for the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} candidates for X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900):

    0++​(n​S)superscript0absent𝑛𝑆0^{++}(nS) states

These constraints are checked for the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} states by using the four-body mass spectrum calculations Wang et al. (2021); Lü et al. (2020) and the branching ratios from Becchi et al. (2020a) updated to include the [6⊗6¯]delimited-[]tensor-product6¯6\left[6\otimes\bar{6}\right] color configuration for the T4​c​(0++)subscript𝑇4𝑐superscript0absentT_{4c}(0^{++}) state. We observe an order of magnitude consistency for Φ(J)​(n​S)∼(0.01÷0.1)similar-tosuperscriptΦ𝐽𝑛𝑆0.010.1\Phi^{(J)}(nS)\sim(0.01\div 0.1) and Br​(T4​c→J/ψ​J/ψ)∼10−3similar-toBr→subscript𝑇4𝑐𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓superscript103\textrm{Br}(T_{4c}\to J/\psi\,J/\psi)\sim 10^{-3}. Considering the two predicted T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} states with masses close to 6900 MeV, namely 0++​(2​S)superscript0absent2𝑆0^{++}(2S) and 2++​(2​S)superscript2absent2𝑆2^{++}(2S), we find the 2++​(2​S)superscript2absent2𝑆2^{++}(2S) state to be the best matching candidate for X​(6900)𝑋6900X(6900).

In the course of future searches extending the first investigations Aaij et al. (2020); Aad et al. (2023); Hayrapetyan et al. (2024), it will be useful to measure the cross-sections of the resonant di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi component (scaled by the unknown branching ratio), such as, for example, σ​(p​p→X​(6900))⋅Br​(J/ψ​J/ψ)⋅𝜎→𝑝𝑝𝑋6900Br𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓\sigma(pp\to X(6900))\cdot\text{Br}(J/\psi\,J/\psi). The comparison of the measured cross-sections with the theoretical predictions can probe the tetraquark nature of the structures observed in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum. A good agreement with the cross-sections obtained by multiplying our results of Table 1 and the model-dependent values of Φ(J)​(n​S)superscriptΦ𝐽𝑛𝑆\Phi^{(J)}(nS) and Br​(J/ψ​J/ψ)Br𝐽𝜓𝐽𝜓\text{Br}(J/\psi\,J/\psi) will hint at a tetraquark nature. In this regard, we encourage experimentalists in ATLAS, CMS and LHCb to conduct the cross-section measurement for the resonant di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi component in the fiducial (pTdi-​J/ψ,ηdi-​J/ψ)superscriptsubscript𝑝𝑇di-𝐽𝜓superscript𝜂di-𝐽𝜓(p_{T}^{\textrm{di-}J/\psi},\>\eta^{\textrm{di-}J/\psi}) volume.

As a final comment, we note that the NLO corrections to the cross-sections might give a sizeable contribution and help mitigate the large scale uncertainty. We also remark that the T4​csubscript𝑇4𝑐T_{4c} production mechanism can be studied via other approaches, for example, by means of kTsubscript𝑘𝑇k_{T}-factorization exploiting the short-distance factors of the order of 𝒪​(αs4)𝒪superscriptsubscript𝛼𝑠4{\cal O}(\alpha_{s}^{4}).
